Lung POCUS: Irregular pleural line with patchy B-lines. Seen in viral (including COVID19) and bacterial pneumonia. This patient had mycoplasma pneumonia. Linear probe used.
Scanning COVID-19 everyday..but not all the B-lines confirm and not all the asymptomatic positives have no pneumonia. We need careful observation to give power to LUS.

2 zones looked like this, the rest A-lines. Dx infectious and with Hx covid suspect.  Subpleural consolidation and B-lines in posterior L upper lung field and R mid axillary

Dynamic Air Bronchograms on Lung on Point of Care Ultrasound. The mesmerizing and oddly satisfying appearance of dynamic air bronchograms on lung ultrasound. A helpful finding to differentiate pneumonia from atelectasis.
Normal Lung Sliding on POCUS
This is a POCUS of a patient with COVID-19. No prior pulmonary disease; had mild tachypnea and mildly low SaO2. US: Irregular pleural line with subpleural nodular consolidation and waterfall B-lines.
COVID19 positive on POCUS
COVID-19 on Lung POCUS
Lung POCUS: Irregular pleural line with B-lines.  Subpleural consolidation better seen with linear probe.
COVID-19 Lung POCUS. Common findings: 1) B lines, 2) Subpleural consolidation, 3) Air bronchograms, 4) Irregular pleural line, 5) Localized pleural effusion.
Lung POCUS: Shred sign in patient with non-translobar consolidation. Phased array probe used.
POCUS in primary care in Madrid - Making decisions with lung ultrasound in COVID19 patients with auscultation and normal oxygen saturation. Change attitude if there is lung involvement

Normal Pleural Lines on Lung Ultrasound. Pleural lines should be sharp and clear, ideally with A-lines showing good aeration. As lung disease occurs this will broaden (? pleural thickening from say asbestos, that looks different) and become thick and lumpy. This is normal.
Pneumonia with fluid and dynamic air bronchograms on Lung POCUS

Lung POCUS: "Hepatization" with fluid bronchograms and dynamic air bronchograms in patient with lobar consolidation due to bacterial pneumonia. Pattern more commonly seen with bacterial pneumonia. Curvilinear probe used.
Normal Lung Sliding in the case of Bullous Lung Disease. Patient presents with with Rt chest pain/dyspnea. hx of Bullous Lung Dz seen on CT.  Concern for PTX.
Multilobar pneumonia is an independent risk factor for increased mortality in CAP.

Air Bronchograms in Pneumonia on Lung Ultrasound. Extreme shortness of breath... pretty easy to appreciate this large pneumonia on POCUS. Here there is consolidation in the distribution of large bronchi, and subtle dynamic air bronchograms.
COVID-19 on Lung POCUS. Initially PCR negative with compatible symptoms, normal xray. Clinically worsened in 48h and repeat PCR  positive.
42 year old diabetic woman with left sided pleuritic chest pain. Mild fever and cough. Left lower lobe consolidation with prominent air bronchograms and a parapneumonic pleural effusion.

54 year old male presenting with collapse while moving couch. The patient is on antibiotics for recent pneumonia diagnosis. Altered mental status in the emergency department. Parasternal long axis of the heart with a large right heart and septum bowing into the left ventricle.

54 year old male presenting with collapse while moving couch. The patient is on antibiotics for recent pneumonia diagnosis. Altered mental status in the emergency department. Parasternal short axis of the heart, again showing a large right heart and a “D” shaped septum consistent with right heart strain.

54 year old male presenting with collapse while moving couch. The patient is on antibiotics for recent pneumonia diagnosis. Altered mental status in the emergency department. Longitudinal view of the IVC shows a plethoric IVC with spontaneous echo contrast.

54 year old male presenting with collapse while moving couch. The patient is on antibiotics for recent pneumonia diagnosis. Altered mental status in the emergency department. Femoral veins were compressed proximally and collapsed, showing no proximal femoral venous DVT.

54 year old male presenting with collapse while moving couch. The patient is on antibiotics for recent pneumonia diagnosis. Altered mental status in the emergency department. After the patient arrested, tPA 50 mg IV bolus was given, ROSC was achieved and the right heart strain is showing improvement.

comment: This patient presented with right upper quadrant pain and a fever. The clinical suspicion was cholecystitis. This RUQ view shows a small area of basal consolidation. The normally reflective aerated lung in the posterior costophrenic angle is lost, and replaced by a tiny pleural effusion surrounding consolidated lung. The “spine sign” is seen and is characteristic of basal pathology. The posterior chest wall is usually obscured by air in normal lung above the diaphragm. In this case the spine can be seen and followed cranially above the diaphragm. This is because ultrasound can penetrate the fluid and solid lung, rather than being reflected away completely.

This patient presented with right upper quadrant pain and a fever. The clinical suspicion was cholecystitis. A second view is taken higher and more laterally over the area of interest in the lower chest wall. This allows direct visualization of the lung rather than looking through liver and diaphragm. A small region of basal consolidation is confirmed, with a surrounding pleural effusion. The patient’s clinical presentation was consistent with a basal pneumonia and the ultrasound features confirmed this. They include consolidated lung, air bronchograms, an irregular “shredded” border between the consolidated and aerated lung, with B-lines at the interface, and an associated small pleural effusion.

This young man presents with high fevers and shortness of breath. He also complains of chest discomfort and an odd feeling in his neck. He is febrile, tachycardic, tachypneoic and hypoxic. There is widespread patchy consolidation which appears to be peripherally based. Similar changes are seen throughout both lung fields. In this case the causative agent is H1N1 Influenza. Among a number of other changes it is known to cause confluent widespread peripherally based consolidation.

This young man presents with high fevers and shortness of breath. He also complains of chest discomfort and an odd feeling in his neck. He is febrile, tachycardic, tachypneoic and hypoxic. Despite significant effort cardiac views were not able to be achieved. Whilst examining the patient subcutaneous crepitus is felt. What do these clips of the patient’s anterior neck show? These show air predominantly deep to sternocleidomastoid. The air is obscuring views of the great neck vessels and deeper tissues. It is seen as a highly reflective interface, resulting in both long path reverberation artefact, short path reverberation artefact and mirror artefact. H1N1 infuenza infection has also been described causing pneumomediastinum and pneumothorax. In this case mediastinal air surrounds the heart and extends up into the neck.

A 40 year old man presented with high fever, tachycardia and vomiting. What do these clips of the upper left chest show? These are both normal views. The first is taken in the axilla and demonstrates normal lung sliding and a single B-line; perhaps from a trace of fluid in the fissure. This is a normal finding. The second clip is taken on the posterior chest wall just medial to the scapula and is also normal. The anterior view taken in the mid-clavicular line was almost identical, again normal. These views show that there is no consolidation involving the ultrasound accessible pleural surfaces in the upper zones. It does not exclude upper zone consolidation that does not touch the pleural surfaces.

A 40 year old man presented with high fever, tachycardia and vomiting. You then move to the posterior lower chest wall. What do these clips show? These views demonstrate a patch of basal consolidation involving the left lower lobe. The diaphragm is seen with the spleen lying below. The consolidated lung fills the costophrenic recess without associated effusion. There is patchy aeration and the irregular consolidation / aerated lung border – the shred sign – is seen.

A patient presents with fever, cough and purulent sputum. There is a well defined patch of consolidation against the posterior chest wall. It is localised and examination elsewhere only reveals normal lung. Where consolidation abuts an interlobar fissure the consolidation / air interface is linear. Otherwise it tends to be irregular and the echogenic interface has a shredded appearance.

A 16 year old woman presents with pleuritic chest pain and a slight sensation of dyspnoea. First you examine the right side of the lung. This is normal lung on the non-painful side. Sliding lung and constantly moving artefact below the pleura are seen and confirm the absence of pneumothorax at the point the transducer is exploring.

A 31 year old male presents after what is thought to be a superficial penetrating chest wound. You perform an ultrasound. You perform an ultrasound scan on the contralateral side of the chest. This is the uninjured side of the chest. This demonstrates normal lung sliding; a comet tail artefact and much more subtle, constantly interrupted A-lines.

A 32 year old man presents with a 4 day history of increasing right sided chest pain and associated shortness of breath. He has no fever, no cough and no sputum production. He is sitting back at 45 degrees. You begin by exploring the 2nd interspace in the mid-clavicular line bilaterally. The first clip taken on the patient’s left side demonstrates normal lung sliding.
